  "published": "2019-03-15",
  "runtimeMin": 45,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, and Rob Harvilla walk the whole uneven career of Ben Affleck: the breakthrough years, each host's personal pinnacle, and Triple Frontier as the latest chapter.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Breakthroughs",
      "note": "where Affleck arrived",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Good Will Hunting",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "Amanda's pick. The 'retainer' job-interview scene, not the tearjerker ending: the supporting wise-ass that launched the Damon-Affleck unit and the Best Original Screenplay win."
        },
        {
          "title": "Chasing Amy",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "Rob's and Sean's pick. Affleck carrying a clunky, badly-aged Kevin Smith movie for nearly two hours, rain confession and visible cameraman included."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dazed and Confused",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "O'Banion, the paddle-wielding bully. Early proof he had no problem playing a shithead."
        },
        {
          "title": "School Ties",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "One of the supporting parts he took just to break in."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mallrats",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Shannon Hamilton, the villain bit part Rob calls one of the best of Affleck's career."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Personal pinnacles",
      "note": "each host's peak Affleck",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Armageddon",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "Amanda's pinnacle (Rob floated it as a breakthrough too). Affleck accepting his blockbuster destiny: the moon-rover fumbling and singing 'Leaving on a Jet Plane' to Liv Tyler, ridiculous and half-winking, which is the good kind."
        },
        {
          "title": "Boiler Room",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "Rob's pinnacle. Peak asshole Affleck taking the Glengarry torch straight from Alec Baldwin: 'I am liquid.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gone Girl",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Rob's other pinnacle. Fincher weaponizing Affleck's blandly handsome self against him for two and a half hours; the shower scene lampoons Argo's."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Town",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "Sean's pinnacle. First time he plays the earnest lead and fully lands it while directing, in an unfussy, mean, Eastwood-flat heist movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gone Baby Gone",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "His directing debut; he stays behind the camera and puts brother Casey out front."
        },
        {
          "title": "Argo",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "Best Picture, no Best Director nod. Sharp and tense but oddly forgettable next to the 'marriage is hard' acceptance speech."
        },
        {
          "title": "Shakespeare in Love",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "Sarcastic, good, and supporting: the kind of role that suited him."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The tough stretches",
      "note": "big swings, more misses",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Pearl Harbor",
          "year": 2001
        },
        {
          "title": "The Sum of All Fears",
          "year": 2002,
          "note": "A bland leading-man Jack Ryan."
        },
        {
          "title": "Changing Lanes",
          "year": 2002,
          "note": "Not a bad movie, him and Samuel L. Jackson, but it landed at an awkward point in his stardom."
        },
        {
          "title": "Daredevil",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "The first time he played a superhero and failed."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gigli",
          "year": 2003
        },
        {
          "title": "Paycheck",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "A literal manifestation of what was going on at the time."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jersey Girl",
          "year": 2004
        },
        {
          "title": "Hollywoodland",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "The supposed serious comeback as George Reeves; Sean wants those hours back."
        },
        {
          "title": "Runner Runner",
          "year": 2013
        },
        {
          "title": "Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "The best thing about a movie he can't rescue."
        },
        {
          "title": "Suicide Squad",
          "year": 2016
        },
        {
          "title": "The Accountant",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Ridiculous, fun, objectively terrible, and, Rob argues, a high-degree-of-difficulty near-Gigli he somehow walks away from upright."
        },
        {
          "title": "Live by Night",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "His first directing job after Argo."
        },
        {
          "title": "Justice League",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Joyless Batman, with no energy and no sign he can't wait to tell his kid about it."
        },
        {
          "title": "200 Cigarettes",
          "year": 1999
        },
        {
          "title": "Forces of Nature",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "As Amanda puts it, we don't need to talk about it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dogma",
          "year": 1999
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Triple Frontier, and what's next",
      "note": "the new thing",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Triple Frontier",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "J.C. Chandor's macho men-on-a-mission jungle heist. A paunchy, worn, cracking-voiced Affleck playing fading masculinity: the role that fits where he actually is."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last Thing He Wanted",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Dee Rees's Netflix Joan Didion adaptation, Anne Hathaway up front and Affleck in support: a wise step down from full-blown star."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Way Back",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Then titled Torrance, a Gavin O'Connor reunion after The Accountant."
        }
      ]
